<TITLE> Kenya's 8 pct growth in '08 now unattainable-cbank </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 NAIROBI, Feb 6 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Kenya's economic growth will fall short of the 8 percent projected for 2008 due to the political crisis and inflation in the first quarter will go up, the central bank governor said on Wednesday. In a statement, Njuguna Ndung'u said the bank would be ready to stabilise the shilling's foreign exchange rate if movements were not based on fundamentals. "The GDP growth for 2008 may however not be as high as the 8 percent that was initially projected. This is because some key sectors like tourism ... have been severely affected," he said. "The CBK (Central Bank of Kenya) is committed to stabilising the exchange rate movement when volatility in the nominal exchange rate is driven by factors other than fundamentals ...," he added. The local shilling's trade versus the dollar for most of January has been volatile, at one time nearly touching a three-year low. Kenya's economy has been expanding by an average 5 percent over the last five years and was projected to grow by 8 percent in 2008 but a post-election crisis that has killed some 1,000 people has affected key sectors of the economy. Ethnic clashes between communities allied to re-elected President Mwai Kibaki and his main opponent have displaced some 304,000 people, mainly in the fertile Rift Valley region that is the country's bread basket. Ndung'u said inflation was likely to rise further in coming months. It jumped to 18.2 percent in January from 12 percent in December mainly from shortages caused by the insecurity. "Food prices are also expected to rise as a result of failed rains in most parts of the country and as a consequence of ethnic cleansing in some parts of the country, some of which are food surplus areas," he sa
